I have never understood the principle of quick sort from my undergraduate studies until today when I learned Haskell and saw a diagram that intuitively explained the principle of quick sort. Here, I will explain the working principle of quick sort based on my understanding.

The concept of quick sort is very simple:

#quote(block: true)[Take an element from the list, and among the remaining elements, select all elements that are smaller than it to place on its left, and the rest on its right.]

At this point, we encounter an obvious problem: the two lists on either side of the "selected" element are still unordered (not sorted) internally, because this step can be understood as traversing the original list, so the order of the elements has not changed.

Here is where the true essence of the quick sort algorithm lies—

#quote(block: true)[For each list, repeat the first step until the lists on either side of the selected element contain at most one element.]

It can be seen that this is a recursive operation. Taking the array `[5, 1, 9, 4, 6, 7, 3]` and the sorting function `quicksort` as an example:

== quicksort begins

To simplify the algorithm, we directly choose the first element as the selected element when we start processing the array. After filtering, our result becomes:

```haskell
quicksort([1, 4, 3]) ++ [5] ++ quicksort([9, 6, 7])
```

The middle `[5]` is our selected element, the left side is the array of elements smaller than it `[1, 4, 3]`, and the right side is the elements larger than it `[9, 6, 7]`. It can be seen that the arrays on both sides of the element are still unordered and still need to be sorted, so in the above pseudocode, it is written as `quicksort(Array)`, which means to continue applying the sorting operation to the two arrays.

Here, taking the left array as an example, let's see how recursion works:

== quicksort first level recursion

For the new array `[1, 4, 3]`, we repeat the above operation, selecting the first element `1` as the selected element and filtering its two sides, resulting in:

```haskell
quicksort([]) ++ [1] ++ quicksort([4, 3])
```

The left side has become an empty array, which means that the selected `1` is the smallest element in the entire array, so there are no elements smaller than it on its left. Thus, only the right side with elements larger than it `[4, 3]` remains, and we still need to apply the sorting operation quicksort:

== quicksort second level recursion

For the new array `[4, 3]`, we repeat the above operation, resulting in:

```haskell
quicksort([3]) ++ [4] ++ quicksort([])
```

At this point, we can say that the depth of recursion stops here. The left side `quicksort([3])` has only one element and does not need further sorting, it will directly return 3, while the right side will return empty. At this point, the above expression completes the sorting:

```haskell
quicksort([3]) ++ [4] ++ quicksort([])
= [3, 4]
```

== quicksort first level recursion

Continuing to return this result:

```haskell
quicksort([]) ++ [1] ++ quicksort([4, 3])
= [1] ++ [3, 4]
= [1, 3, 4]
```

== quicksort top level

Continuing to return:

```haskell
quicksort([1, 4, 3]) ++ [5] ++ quicksort([9, 6, 7])
= [1, 3, 4] ++ [5] ++ quicksort([9, 6, 7])
= [1, 3, 4, 5] ++ quicksort([9, 6, 7])
```

Applying the same operation to the right side of the original expression `quicksort([9, 6, 7])`, we will ultimately get the sorted array: `[6, 7, 9]`. Substituting into the expression:

```haskell
[1, 3, 4, 5] ++ quicksort([9, 6, 7])
= [1, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 9]
```

Mission accomplished!

At this point, the entire quick sort algorithm process is complete. Finally, I will include the diagram that helped me understand the algorithm and my Haskell implementation, hoping that everyone can easily grasp quick sort through this article.

#figure(image("/public/assets/img/2018/05/quicksort.png"), caption: "Quick Sort Diagram")

```haskell
quicksort :: (Ord a) => [a] -> [a]
quicksort [] = []
quicksort (x:xs) =
  lessthan ++ [x] ++ largerthan
  where lessthan = quicksort [a | a <- xs, a < x]
        largerthan = quicksort [a | a <- xs, a >= x]
```
